      <?php include "0.php";?> and later that year the child was born, in a busy urban hospital on the sunny autumn morning of September 23, 1985. If he&rsquo;d been a girl, his parents would have named him Megan, but instead his parents named him William.</p>
      <p>Thirty-two years later he was hanging from an airlock in a spacesuit on a spacewalk on the international space station, squinting, grinning, chattering into a radio in the dazzling sunlight as the space station drifted through orbit above the ocean when the space station suddenly exploded, blasting him backward through the atmosphere screaming and shouting and gasping in shock. For a moment there was a constellation of shimmering mylar and titanium and aluminum and steel debris where the space station had been, and then the wreckage seemed simultaneously to glitter and ripple and fade into the darkness of the atmosphere, and then he was alone, soaring through orbit faster than the speed of sound, and he realized that there was no hope for him, none, nothing. The radio had no signal. For hours he floated in silence through the darkness of the atmosphere, thinking about his mother and thinking about his father and thinking about how his life could have been different, gazing at the planet below. For a while he cried because the planet was so beautiful, not sobbing or weeping but just staring at the planet with tears trickling down his cheeks, breathing, and then the feeling was gone, and afterward all that remained were questions without answers. Eventually the oxygen tank hit one percent. Eventually the oxygen tank hit zero percent. He died there in the sky.</p>
